 evolved. From the colonization of Turtle Island in the 1500s to problematic activist practices by would-be settler allies today, Adam Barker traces the trajectory of settler colonialism, drawing out details of its operation and unflinchingly identifying its weaknesses. Making and Breaking Settler Space proposes an innovative, unified spatial theory of settler colonization in Canada and the United States. In doing so, it offers a framework within which settlers can pursue decolonial actions in solidarity with Indigenous communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColonization. 0aDecolonizationzCanada. 0aDecolonizationzNorth America. 0aDecolonizationzUnited States. 0aImperialism. 0aIndigenous peoplesxColonizationzCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxColonizationzUnited States. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLand tenurezNorth America. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxColonization. 0aIndigenous peopleszNorth AmericaxSocial conditions. 0aIndigenous peopleszNorth America. 0aSettler colonialismzCanada. 0aSettler colonialismzNorth America. 0aSettler colonialismzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486542540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774865425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774865425/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-141764-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aG